<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="sec-exam2-study-guide" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Study Guide: Exam 2</title>
  <p>Book sections: 6-8, 10-11</p>
  <p>
    Things to know:
    <ol>
      <li>Why were roboticists interested in emulating animal behavior?</li>
      <li>Describe the three levels of a computational theory and in what ways each of them is comparing animal behavior to robot behavior.</li>
      <li>Reflexive behaviors can be classified broadly in three types: reflexes, taxes, and fixed-action patterns. Describe how each type behaves and provide concrete examples.</li>
      <li>Describe the concept of <em>affordance</em> and provide examples of visual as well as non-visual affordances.</li>
      <li>Describe the four types of innate releasing mechanisms and provide examples.</li>
      <li>Describe the different primitive types of potential fields and in what circumstances each would be appropriate.</li>
      <li>Describe what a magnitude profile is and what is its purpose, and describe specific magnitude profiles.</li>
      <li>Describe the main ideas around "subsumption" as a mechanism for coordinating behaviors.</li>
      <li>Describe using a FSA a real-world process (like for example the process of getting your car out of a closed garage and onto the main road).</li>
      <li>Describe the differences between active and passive sensors. Provide examples of each.</li>
      <li>What are the three types of sensor usage? Describe each. (e.g. proprioception is one)</li>
      <li>What are the options for sensors involved in odometry? How are they classified in terms of type of output? What are the advantages and disadvantages of each?</li>
      <li>What are the options for proximity sensors? What are the advantages and disadvantages of each?</li>
      <li>Discuss the different color spaces that can be used to represent colors, and how they each measure a color's effect.</li>
      <li>Describe at a high level the techniques of region segmentation and of color histogramming.</li>
      <li>Explain the concept of a "logical sensor" and how it varies from physical sensors.</li>
      <li>Explain the difference between physical redundancy and logical redundancy in sensors.</li>
      <li>What are factors to consider when designing the sensor suite for a robot?</li>
      <li>Explain at a high level how a stereo pair of cameras can achieve a sense of the depth/distance of objects.</li>
      <li>Describe some of the challenges encountered when using sonar sensors for distance detection.</li>
    </ol>
  </p>
</section>
